Alias concept: 

Threat actors and malware names have aliases. That is other names that they are known as. Different security vendors may track things by different names. For this next one, keep in mind that ProofPoint tracks it as ZPHP, while others track it as SmartApe or SmartApeSG. It’s important to understand the alias concept so that you know you’re talking about the same thing with other people.

For ZPHP, we will use Proofpoint ET as our intel lead again.

Search the Ruleset Update Summary lists for ZPHP. 

[https://community.emergingthreats.net/search?q=ZPHP%20order%3Alatest](https://community.emergingthreats.net/search?q=ZPHP%20order%3Alatest)

![](data:image/png;base64,)

I’m using the link below.

[https://community.emergingthreats.net/t/ruleset-update-summary-2025-10-08-v11035/3077](https://community.emergingthreats.net/t/ruleset-update-summary-2025-10-08-v11035/3077)

![](data:image/png;base64,)

I’ll analyze the domain yungask[.]com. Search for that domain in urlscan.

[https://urlscan.io/search/#yungask.com](https://urlscan.io/search/#yungask.com)

![](data:image/png;base64,)

You’ll need to find a scan task that occurred around the same time of the lead reporting. Timing is important because if you check 5 years later, it may be repurposed for something else. Also, you’ll want to find the scan task with a 200 (OK) response code. If you’re following along with my example, it’ll be result #8 from the results snip above.

You can access the scan result from the link below.

[https://urlscan.io/result/0199c842-4106-7359-bc02-c2c094af5bce/](https://urlscan.io/result/0199c842-4106-7359-bc02-c2c094af5bce/)

![](data:image/png;base64,)

In the snip above, we can see the page title is “Activatar | Template”. I’ve analyzed this a long time ago, and I’ve observed this is a template. Specifically, this is a template for a gym website. We can find other websites that use this template by simply searching for the page title.

This is the urlscan search query below.
page.title:"Activitar | Template"

This is the search link below.

[https://urlscan.io/search/#page.title%3A%22Activitar%20%7C%20Template%22](https://urlscan.io/search/#page.title%3A%22Activitar%20%7C%20Template%22)

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Click the details button that is below the “? Help” button. You will need to see the ASN associated with the IP. For example, in the snip above, result #2 shows the ASN is 202015, and result #4 is ASN 14956. The AS stands for Autonomous System, and the N stands for Number. It could be referenced in many ways such as ASN202015,  AS202015,  or just 202015. The AS is the network that the IP originates from. This information will be used to narrow our findings.

In the snip above, we can see result #1 is on a Cloudflare server. This is likely not related. Remember that the template is for gym websites. Result #1 has a domain name that would indicate it is used to join a health club, or gym. 

That leaves us with the domain from result #4: foolowme[.]com that is hosted on AS14956.

Follow the validation method from the TA2726 section, and check the comments for the domain in VT.

[https://www.virustotal.com/gui/domain/foolowme.com/community](https://www.virustotal.com/gui/domain/foolowme.com/community)

![](data:image/png;base64,)

We can see that JaffaCakes118 posted that this was reported as the FAKEUPDATES malware in THREATfox. We can see the ZPHP tag is included. This external validation is successful. We will need to observe its behavior so that we can perform a first-hand validation.

Return to the earlier search.

[https://urlscan.io/search/#yungask.com](https://urlscan.io/search/#yungask.com)

![](data:image/png;base64,)

I will analyze result #1. I need to observe the resource that is called. Click the HTTP tab to view the transactions. Search for the ZPHP domain to view the requested resource. 

[https://urlscan.io/result/0199cdfd-451e-72ed-bbc3-aa3c464113bc/#transactions](https://urlscan.io/result/0199cdfd-451e-72ed-bbc3-aa3c464113bc/#transactions)

In the snip below, we can see that the compromised site will request the “/work/original.js” resource from the ZPHP domain.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

That is the validation behavior. Let’s validate the domain foolowme[.]com. Go back to the search page.

[https://urlscan.io/search/#foolowme.com](https://urlscan.io/search/#foolowme.com)

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Pick any scan job of a compromised site and find the transaction request (click the HTTP tab and search for the ZPHP domain).

[https://urlscan.io/result/0199c52a-8c61-7001-b3be-8bf39b8de012/#transactions](https://urlscan.io/result/0199c52a-8c61-7001-b3be-8bf39b8de012/#transactions)

![](data:image/png;base64,)

In the snip above, we confirm the validation request for “/work/original.js” from the ZPHP domain. This is a successful first-hand validation. Our next problem to tackle is crafting a query to specify the two ASNs we observe ZPHP threat actors using (AS202015 and AS14956).

The query below will address our needs.
page.title:"Activitar | Template" AND asn:(AS202015 OR AS14956)
[https://urlscan.io/search/#page.title%3A%22Activitar%20%7C%20Template%22%20AND%20asn%3A(AS202015%20OR%20AS14956)](https://urlscan.io/search/#page.title%3A%22Activitar%20%7C%20Template%22%20AND%20asn%3A\(AS202015%20OR%20AS14956\))

![](data:image/png;base64,)

In the snip above, you can see it also includes another ZPHP domain pomofight[.]com.

This is a success so far. Now we must address the next problem. What happens if the ZPHP threat actors start using a new template? What happens if the ZPHP threat actors start using a new AS? You can address these problems by continuously monitoring the threat actor activities. You can monitor first-hand, and external. 

For the first-hand monitoring, you can select a compromised site, and monitor for changes. In a previous snip that I showed for the compromised site pemptousia[.]com, there were two requests for “/work/original.js”. See below.

[https://urlscan.io/result/0199cdfd-451e-72ed-bbc3-aa3c464113bc/#transactions](https://urlscan.io/result/0199cdfd-451e-72ed-bbc3-aa3c464113bc/#transactions)

![](data:image/png;base64,)

In the snip above, we can see that there is also the ZPHP request to pablogutierrez[.]life.

In THREATfox, we can see that HuntYethHounds reported it as SmartApeSG back on 07JAN25.

[https://threatfox.abuse.ch/browse.php?search=ioc%3Apablogutierrez.life](https://threatfox.abuse.ch/browse.php?search=ioc%3Apablogutierrez.life)

![](data:image/png;base64,)

We can use this observation, and monitor compromised sites for updates to the ZPHP domain that they use. That is the technique to monitor first-hand.

We’ve already used Proofpoint as an intel lead for TA2726 domains, and for ZPHP domains. I’ve just introduced the validation technique of using THREATfox. We can also use THREATfox as an intel lead to monitor for changes. 

When you monitor any threat, you will need to know the aliases. ZPHP and SmartApeSG are the main names used for this specific threat. You can monitor the ZPHP tag in THREATfox using the link below.

[https://threatfox.abuse.ch/browse/tag/ZPHP/](https://threatfox.abuse.ch/browse/tag/ZPHP/)

![](data:image/png;base64,)

You can monitor the SmartApeSG tag using the link below.

[https://threatfox.abuse.ch/browse/tag/SmartApeSG/](https://threatfox.abuse.ch/browse/tag/SmartApeSG/)

![](data:image/png;base64,)

In this section we’ve used Proofpoint ET as an intel lead and we’ve learned how to use THREATfox as an intel lead. We validated first-hand by checking the request patterns from compromised sites. We validated external by checking VT comments and THREATfox. We’ve learned how to pivot on the page title because the threat actors use a gym-themed template. We’ve learned how to scope the monitoring query to limit the ASNs to known-bad ASNs that the threat actor uses. We’ve learned how to continuously monitor threat actor activity by monitoring compromised sites for new requests.
